                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14479368" author="paulk" created="Wed, 1 Dec 2010 07:10:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I have removed the ClassCastException with a compile time error saying that the multiple assignment isn&apos;t currently supported. We now need to decide if we want to support that form.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14470514" author="hamlet.darcy@canoo.com" created="Wed, 1 Dec 2010 07:21:54 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks Paul. Is there a reason not to support multiple assignments on @Field? Is it hard to implement?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14479366" author="paulk" created="Thu, 2 Dec 2010 06:29:42 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;It is a little tricky but not impossible. There are arguments for and against. I guess the fact that we don&apos;t support such syntax for normal class fields worries me a little. I.e. the following is not currently allowed:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;class &lt;/span&gt;Foo {
  def (bar, baz) = [1, 2]
}
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, in some sense we are providing a backdoor way to write such things for the main script class.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14470550" author="hamlet.darcy@canoo.com" created="Thu, 2 Dec 2010 08:03:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;seems reasonable to disallow it then. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14479374" author="paulk" created="Thu, 2 Dec 2010 15:51:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Let&apos;s close it then for now. Someone can always make a strong case for why we should go further.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
